        <section class="body">
          <div id="b_h">
            <div class="main-wt no-border">
              <h4 class="main-wt-title">
                <span>Hormone</span>
              </h4>
              <ul class="btm-spc">
                <li>
                  <h4>Testosterone</h4>
                </li>
                <li>Recover and strengthen muscles</li>
                <li>If you finish your workout with high-intensity weight training rather than cardio, testosterone
                  lasts for an additional hour after the workout</li>
                <li class="btm-spc">It has effects such as increasing libido, bone density, metabolism, and losing fat
                </li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Growth Hormone</h4>
                </li>
                <li></li>
                <li>Builds muscle, boosts the immune system, and breaks down fat</li>
                <li class="btm-spc"><strong>Taking an early sleep (most secreted between 10 and 1 am)</strong> and
                  <strong>high intensity exercise</strong>is effective in promoting growth hormone</li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Cortisol</h4>
                </li>
                <li>Breaks down muscle, raising blood sugar and storing it as fat</li>
                <li class="btm-spc">
                  <div class="bottom-15px">When stressed, cortisol is released, and high stress triggers dopamine to
                    consume refined carbohydrates or sugars</div>
                  <div>This raises blood sugar, and the body secretes insulin to lower blood sugar. Due to the blood
                    sugar lowered by insulin, the body secretes cortisol again, and when this is repeated, you gain
                    weight</div>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Insulin</h4>
                </li>
                <li>Hormone that lowers blood sugar, regulates glucose and fat metabolism, and transports glucose to
                  muscles</li>
                <li>
                  <div class="btm-15px">Insulin stores excess glucose as glycogen, and any excess glucose is stored as
                    fat.</div>
                  <div>When you exercise, insulin is very beneficial because it uses up enough energy stored in
                    glycogen. But if you don't exercise, you will gain weight. So I strongly recommend weight training
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li class="btm-spc">Excreted within 20-30 minutes after eating</li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Glucagon</h4>
                </li>
                <li>Raises blood sugar and breaks down fat</li>
                <li>
                  <div class="btm-15px">When you eat rice, your blood sugar rises and insulin is secreted. Energy is
                    then stored in glycogen and fat</div>
                  <div>After a certain period of time, blood sugar levels decrease. At this time, glucagon acts to raise
                    blood sugar and break down glycogen and fat</div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <div class="btm-15px">Glucagon is secreted within 1 hour after insulin secretion during the day, but 5
                    hours after insulin secretion at night</div>
                  <div>Reason why you gain weight if you eat late-night snacks</div>
                </li>
              </ul>


              <ul class="btm-spc">
                <li>
                  <h4>Peptide</h4>
                </li>
                <li class="btm-spc">Reduces appetite and promotes satiety</li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Leptin</h4>
                </li>
                <li class="btm-spc">Suppresses appetite and regulates energy balance</li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Ghrelin</h4>
                </li>
                <li>Stimulates the appetite</li>
                <li class="btm-spc"><strong>If you eat healthy and sleep well, it will function normally</strong></li>
              </ul>

              <ul class="btm-spc">
                <li>
                  <h4>Dopamine</h4>
                </li>
                <li>It has many functions, including reward system, motivation, sleep, sense of achievement, and
                  stimulation or inhibition of motor neurons</li>
                <li>The more dopamine is secreted, the more we feel pleasure, and we feel motivation, happiness,
                  achievement, joy, and emotion</li>
                <li class="btm-spc"><strong>Exercise, protein intake (dairy, legumes), small goal setting/reward, music,
                    cold shower, sunlight</strong>is effective in increasing dopamine
                </li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Serotonin</h4>
                </li>
                <li>Commonly known as the happiness hormone, it is a molecule that makes you feel happy</li>
                <li>It stimulates the motor nerves of the spinal cord that excite the antigravity muscles. In other
                  words, the spinal muscles become straight and the face becomes lively</li>
                <li>Inhibits dopamine and noradrenaline neurons and creates a sense of calm</li>
                <li class="btm-spc"><strong>Exercise, sunshine, positive thinking, good vibes</strong>is effective in
                  increasing serotonin</li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Endorphins</h4>
                </li>
                <li class="btm-spc">Pain relief, uplifting emotions</li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Melatonin</h4>
                </li>
                <li class="btm-spc">Serotonin secreted during the day is converted to melatonin at night, improving
                  sleep quality.</li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Oxytocin</h4>
                </li>
                <li>Commonly known as the love hormone, it makes us feel trust, love, decrease anxiety, bonding, and
                  self-control.</li>
                <li class="btm-spc">Exercise, physical contact, meditation, and emotional behaviors(encouragement,
                  praise, etc.) are effective in boosting oxytocin</li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Epinephrine(adrenaline)</h4>
                </li>
                <li>Prepares the body to respond quickly to threats</li>
                <li>
                  <div>Increases blood pressure and makes the heart beat faster</div>
                  <div>It slows digestion and concentrates oxygen and glucose to the brain and muscles. The liver breaks
                    down glucose into glycogen, which raises blood sugar and breaks down fat</div>
                </li>
                <li class="btm-spc">Epinephrine is secreted during exercise or emergency situations</li>

                <li>
                  <h4>Norepinephrine</h4>
                </li>
                <li>Increases concentration, strains the body, regulates emotional harmony</li>
                <li class="btm-spc">
                  <div>Stress activates the sympathetic nervous system, which is the autonomic nervous system. The
                    activated sympathetic nervous system excessively secretes norepinephrine and melanin absorbs it
                  </div>
                  <div>Norepinephrine induces cell division of melanocytes and loses their function as a pigment source.
                    Which makes white hair</div>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
